The problem requires approximating \(P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) where \(\bar{X}\) is the sample mean of a random sample of size \(n = 12\) from a uniform distribution on the interval \((0,1)\).

For a uniform distribution on \((0,1)\), the mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and the variance \(\sigma^2 = 1/12\). The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) has mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2/n = (1/12)/12 = 1/144\), so the standard deviation is \(\sqrt{1/144} = 1/12\).

By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed since \(n = 12\) is sufficiently large. The probability \(P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) is standardized using the Z-score formula:
\[
Z = \frac{\bar{X} - \mu}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}} = \frac{\bar{X} - 0.5}{1/12}.
\]

For the lower bound \(\bar{X} = 1/2\):
\[
Z_{\text{lower}} = \frac{0.5 - 0.5}{1/12} = 0.
\]

For the upper bound \(\bar{X} = 2/3\):
\[
Z_{\text{upper}} = \frac{2/3 - 0.5}{1/12} = \frac{1/6}{1/12} = 2.
\]

Thus, the probability is approximately \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\) where \(Z\) is a standard normal random variable. Using standard normal distribution values:
\[
P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = \Phi(2) - \Phi(0) \approx 0.97725 - 0.5 = 0.47725.
\]

Rounding to three decimal places gives 0.477.

