**************
The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds eight, given that each drug has a success probability of \(p_1 = p_2 = p_3 = 0.7\) and there are \(n = 10\) triples (so each drug is tested 10 times). The successes are independent.

For a single drug, the number of successes \(S_i\) follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\). The probability that \(S_i > 8\) (i.e., \(S_i \geq 9\)) is:
\[
P(S_i \geq 9) = P(S_i = 9) + P(S_i = 10)
\]
\[
P(S_i = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3)^1 = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times 0.3 \approx 0.121060821
\]
\[
P(S_i = 10) = (0.7)^{10} \approx 0.0282475249
\]
\[
P(S_i \geq 9) \approx 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459
\]

The probability that \(S_i \leq 8\) is:
\[
P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_i \geq 9) \approx 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541
\]

Since the drugs are independent, the probability that all three drugs have at most 8 successes is:
\[
P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = [P(S_i \leq 8)]^3 \approx (0.8506916541)^3 \approx 0.6156244336
\]

Thus, the probability that the maximum exceeds 8 is:
\[
P(\max S_i > 8) = 1 - P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) \approx 1 - 0.6156244336 = 0.3843755664
\]

Rounded to three decimal places for reasonable significant figures, the probability is 0.384.

