Problem: The positron has charge $+e$ and mass equal to the electron mass. Calculate in electronvolts the ground-state energy of positronium-an "atom" that consists of a positron and an electron. The unit of the answer should be $\mathrm{eV}$.
Solution: The ground-state energy of positronium is calculated based on the reduced mass of the electron-positron system. Since both particles have the same mass, \( m_e \), the reduced mass \( \mu = \frac{m_e}{2} \). For a hydrogen-like atom, the ground-state energy scales with the reduced mass. The ground-state energy of hydrogen is \(-13.6  \text{eV}\), and for positronium, it is reduced by the ratio of the reduced masses:

\[
E_{\text{pos}} = E_H \times \frac{\mu_{\text{pos}}}{\mu_H} = -13.6 \times \frac{m_e / 2}{m_e} = -13.6 \times \frac{1}{2} = -6.8  \text{eV}
\]

The value is rounded to two significant figures, consistent with the precision of the hydrogen ground-state energy (\(13.6\) eV).

